{"title_page": "Beelden aan Zee", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2011}}\n{{coord|52|6|38|N|4|16|39|E|type:landmark_region:NL|display=title}}\n\n[[Image:April 2004 Beeld Scheveningen.JPG|right|thumb|Sculpture by [[Igor Mitoraj]] on the Boulevard]]\n\n'''Beelden aan Zee''' (\"Images/sculptures by the sea\") museum in the [[Scheveningen]] district of [[The Hague]], founded in 1994 by the sculpture collectors Theo and Lida Scholten, is the only Dutch museum which specializes in exhibiting [[sculpture]].\n\nThe museum shows contemporary international and national sculpture. The curators organize new [[art exhibition|exhibitions]] three or more times per year in its large circular main space. Exhibitions are created on themes such as the 2010 exhibitions, \"Unwanted Land\" exhibition by 6 contemporary artists or the \"Fathers and Sons\" show, or exhibitions around a particular artist.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} The museum features works by [[Karel Appel]], [[Wim Quist]], [[Man Ray]], and [[Fritz Koenig]]. The mission of the museum is to use a mix of forms and materials in the works express \"the human experience.\"<ref name=\"Dunford2010\"/>\n\nSince 2004, the museum building also houses the ''Sculptuur Instituut'' (\"Sculpture Institute\"), a [[research institute]] on contemporary sculpture. The institute library is accessible during museum opening hours.\n\n==The building==\nThe museum building was designed by architect Wim Quist, underneath the historic \"Pavilion of Wied\" [[William I of the Netherlands|King William I]] built in 1826 for his wife, Princess Wilhelmine of Prussia.<ref name=\"Dunford2010\">{{cite book|author=Martin Dunford|title=The Rough Guide to The Netherlands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8j03xxJasTMC&pg=PA393|accessdate=24 November 2011|year=2010|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-84836-882-8|page=169}}</ref> Before construction started, the municipality of The Hague required that the museum not be visible from the dunes. The museum has accordingly been built entirely underground, with terraces on the dune, which are also not visible from a distance. The museum is also not visible from the boulevard.  From the roof of the museum one can see the sea, but not the boulevard nor the Scheveningen beach. As a result, the museum can be hard to find although it is signposted from the end of the street. \nThe concrete and glass museum has an unusual slot-system in the concrete walls designed by the architect, so that sculpture or paintings can be hung from a bolt set into one of the many blocks in the walls. The whole museum is built on various levels with light coming in from above in many spaces. It includes a number of outdoor areas and museum supplies raincoats for visitors. There is also a cafe and a bookshop, as well as facilities for the disabled.\n\n<!-- translation difficulties in this paragraph\nThe partitions of the museum its concrete, with in each block-system a propeller breach, where smaller beelden to be confirmed can. The breaches with propeller wire sat from the beginning, because let flow them necessary to the concrete in the mal, whereupon it were just concrete block-systems became. The floor is of a sandy stone.\n-->\n\n==Tom Otterness: Fairy Tale Sculptures by the Sea==\nA public [[sculpture garden]] created out of numerous sculptures by the American sculptor [[Tom Otterness]] is located on the boulevard just beyond the museum. This \"fairy tale pictures to the sea\" installation was designed in particular for children to enjoy.\n<gallery>\nImage:Scheveningen Beelden aan zee.jpg\nImage:Otterness_RC046.jpg\nImage:FTAT_1.jpg\nImage:FTAT_2.jpg\nImage:FTAT_3.jpg\nImage:FTAT_4.jpg\nImage:FTAT_5.jpg\nImage:FTAT_6.jpg\nImage:FTAT_7.jpg\nImage:FTAT_8.jpg\nImage:FTAT_9.jpg\nImage:FTAT_10.jpg\nImage:STAT_11.jpg\nImage:STAT_12.jpg\nImage:FTAT_17.jpg\nImage:STAT_14.jpg|''Tom Otterness sculpture garden''\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Beelden aan Zee}}\n*[http://www.beeldenaanzee.nl Official web site] {{in lang|nl}}\n*[http://www.sculptuurinstituut.nl Sculpture institute] {{in lang|nl}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130121074410/http://www.tomostudio.com/exhibitions_fairytales.html Website Tom Otterness]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sculpture galleries]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Museums in The Hague]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Sculpture gardens, trails and parks in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=November 2011}}\n{{coord|52|6|38|N|4|16|39|E|type:landmark_region:NL|display=title}}\n\n[[Image:April 2004 Beeld Scheveningen.JPG|right|thumb|Sculpture by [[Igor Mitoraj]] on the Boulevard]]\n\n'''Beelden aan Zee''' (\"Images/sculptures by the sea\") museum in the [[Scheveningen]] district of [[The Hague]], founded in 1994 by the sculpture collectors Theo and Lida Scholten, is the only Dutch museum which specializes in exhibiting [[sculpture]]. \n\nThe museum shows contemporary international and national sculpture. The curators organize new [[art exhibition|exhibitions]] three or more times per year in its large circular main space. Exhibitions are created on themes such as the 2010 exhibitions, \"Unwanted Land\" exhibition by 6 contemporary artists or the \"Fathers and Sons\" show, or exhibitions around a particular artist.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} The museum features works by [[Karel Appel]], [[Wim Quist]], [[Man Ray]], and [[Fritz Koenig]]. The mission of the museum is to use a mix of forms and materials in the works express \"the human experience.\"<ref name=\"Dunford2010\"/>\n\nSince 2004, the museum building also houses the ''Sculptuur Instituut'' (\"Sculpture Institute\"), a [[research institute]] on contemporary sculpture. The institute library is accessible during museum opening hours.\n\n==The building==\nThe museum b